author: Inside Edition
description: Diane Keaton's death certificate lists her cause of death as "primary bacterial pneumonia." It also reveals that her physician, who specialized in treating people with Alzheimer's, visited the actress two days before her death. NewsNation's Paula Froelich tells Inside Edition's Les Trent that for the past couple years, Keaton was battling dementia and Alzheimer's. Froelich also says Keaton had to wear an ear piece while filming one of her last movies, the 2023 romantic comedy "Maybe I Do."
title: Did Diane Keaton Battle With Dementia And Alzheimer's?

author: Inside Edition
description: A terrifying encounter took place in Virginia where three masked strangers approached the front door of a home and threatened to kill the homeowners while demanding to come inside. As investigators continue the search for the trio, some are wondering if the encounter was inspired by a scene in the tv show "Task," a fictional HBO crime series starring Mark Ruffalo. Police say they remain hot on the trail of the veiled vagrants.
title: Was This Terrifying Encounter By Masked Trio Inspired By A TV Show?

author: Inside Edition
description: America's fastest-growing sport is leading to a major increase in eye injuries. A new medical study shows that emergency room visits by pickleball players with eye injuries hit 1,262 last year, three times higher than just a few years ago. How can you cut the risk? Inside Edition tried out impact-resistant safety glasses like the ones many players wear for racquetball or squash. Ophthalmologist Dr. Jonathan Tsui, who co-authored the study, tells Inside Edition eye injuries are causing concern.
title: Pickleball Is Leading To Major Rise In Eye Injuries

author: Inside Edition
description: A man coming out of a gas station took off in a stolen car. A frantic mother called 911. Her baby was in the backseat of the car. In a shocking turn of events, the carjacker backed up the car. The suspects returned to the gas station because he realized the woman's 1-year-old baby was in the back seat. The car-jacker who had second thoughts about his misdeed was taken into custody.
title: Carjacker Returns Car After Realizing Baby Is In Back Seat

author: Inside Edition
description: Bella Hadid's Victoria's Secret appearance is sparking speculation that something may have been wrong as she came down the runway. Fans say she seemed unsteady, her eyes looking downcast. Last month, Hadid posted photos from her hospital bed as she deals with debilitating Lyme Disease. She was diagnosed in 2013. Hadid reacted to the reports, Friday, admitting it was not easy striding the runway with giant wings.
title: Model Bella Hadid Responds To Concerns About Her Health

author: Inside Edition
description: Police say Keon King, who cops say is a menace to society, kidnapped 23-year-old Kada Scott, a healthcare worker and aspiring model from Philadelphia. She vanished two weeks ago after finishing her shift at an assisted living facility. Investigators believe King was stalking her online where she posted weekly videos about her life. King is in custody, but Scott's fate remains a mystery and the search for her is becoming more desperate by the day. Her parents fear the worst.
title: 'Menace To Society' In Custody During Search For Missing Woman: Cops

author: Inside Edition
description: Two siblings learned that a shopping trip for new phones was actually to buy the old fashion kind, a landline phone. Parker Schultz, 9, and his 10-year-old sister Paisley were really upset. Their mother, Courtney, made the unconventional call. Courtney says the landline phones still allow her kids to have plenty of conversations with friends. The family is part of a new trend where parents worried about what cell phones could do to their kids' mental health, say “no” to cell phones.
title: Mom Reveals To Kids They’re Shopping For Landline Phone, Not Cell Phones

author: Inside Edition
description: Anthony Antonucci believes he escaped certain death at the hands of John Wayne Gacy. He spoke out Friday as a new drama about Gacy, "Devil in Disguise: John Wayne Gacy," debuts on Peacock. Antonucci was 16, working part-time for Gacy's construction company, when Gacy challenged him to a wrestling contest. It was a trick Gacy used on many of his victims, but Antonucci, a high school wrestler, managed to wriggle out of the cuffs and turn the tables, slapping them on Gacy.
title: Man Who Survived Killer Clown John Wayne Gacy Speaks Out

author: Inside Edition
description: Anyssa Zancanella was rushed to a hospital in Utah six years ago after her water broke. The family says the nurses were so green, they gave her dangerous doses of a labor-inducing drug. They also say the on-call obstetrician was taking a nap in another room. The family says the nurses did not notice the troubling warning signs that the newborn was in distress. Zancanella sued the hospital for malpractice. A judge awarded the family close to $1 billion.
title: Judge Awards Family Close To $1 Billion After Botched Baby Delivery

author: Inside Edition
description:
Sponsored Content by RoC Skincare.

Inside Edition teamed up with RoC® Skincare and its partner, dermatologist Dr. Lindsey Zubritsky, for tips on how you could get fuller lips. She says getting lip injections means using a needle to inject a filler into the lips, which can be painful, costly, and could cause deformations in the lips. Dr. Zubritsky recommends Roc's new Lip Volumizer as a non-invasive treatment for plumper lips.
title: Plump It Up: Needle-Free Tip from Dermatologist For Fuller Lips

author: Inside Edition
description: A driver was lucky to have been spotted by this officer, who rushed to help her in her time of need. The Mesquite Police Department in Texas released this video from the incident. It says the officer driving on a highway saw a car on the other side of the road, but he followed it until he could catch up to see what was going on. When he did come upon the vehicle, it was engulfed in flames with the driver still inside crying out in pain. Inside Edition Digital’s Mara Montalbano has more.
title: Officer Pulls Woman From Burning Car On Texas Highway

author: Inside Edition
description: My, what big feet they had! Researchers say these are dinosaur tracks, created by a sauropod more than 160 million years ago. They were found at an old mining site in Oxfordshire, England, where paleontologists are buzzing with this exciting find in their own country. Inside Edition Digital’s Mara Montalbano has more.
title: 160 Million-Year-Old Dinosaur Footprints Uncovered In England

author: Inside Edition
description: A pesky little feline did not want to be left behind when his family went on vacation. Ray Ray the cat stowed away on the foot of the car. Margaret Denardo and her family stopped for gas when they discovered their cat. They were two hours into their road trip and 100 miles away from home and couldn't turn around, so Ray Ray got to stay. Denardo documented his whole travel adventure through New England and New York City.
title: Cat Sneaks Into His Family's Vacation

author: Inside Edition
description: Clint Buffinton found an old Dr. Pepper bottle while on vacation in the Bahamas with a message inside. Buffington was on vacation from Utah and he happens to be an expert on messages in a bottle. He's found 140 of them. He took the bottle home to Utah and got the message out of the bottle. The massage was handwritten on a brown paper bag and was barely legible. The message said "If found please call or write John Forsyth. Forsyth's family got in touch with Buffington.
title: Man Finds Message In Bottle Tossed In Ocean Decades Ago
